column10: NOTES

We have determined that the longsolid and round hickorynut are threatened species due to the following threats: habitat degradation or loss (Factor A) from a variety of sources (e.g., dams and other barriers, resource extraction); degraded water quality from chemical contamination and erosion from development, agriculture, mining, and forest conversion (Factor A); direct mortality from dredging (Factor E); residual impacts (reduced population size) from historical harvest (Factor B); and the proliferation of invasive, nonnative species (Factor E). These threats also contribute to the negative effects associated with the species’ small population sizes (Factor E).

Primary Threats As summarized in more detail in the assessment report, we focused our analysis of the Sacramento Mountains checkerspot butterfly’s viability on five primary and several secondary factors.  Primary factors include altered wildfire regimes, climate change, incompatible grazing, invasive plants, and recreation.  Secondary factors include collection, disease, parasites and 2023 Recovery Outline for the Sacramento Mountains Checkerspot Butterfly 7 predation, insecticide application, anthropogenic development and ungulate grazing.
